   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Effective system put in place for tracking detainees (Yes/No); 
2. # correctional staff trained to operate system (pre- and post-tests)
3. #Inmates classified and assessed in four (4) pilot facilities with guidelines established; 
4. % change in Correctional Centers population during project period; # skills training facilities established/refurbished; 
5. #inmates engaged in production and earning scheme; profit/savings for prisons 
6. #Correctional Officers and sentenced prisoners certified
7. New Correctional Rules developed (Yes/No);
8. # correctional facilities benefiting from human right audit exercise;  
9. % inmates having access to basic health care services within Correctional facilities; 
8. # new counselors and social workers recruited and capacity improved for the reformation and rehabilitation of inmates.</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2016">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Basic file management system in some correctional facilities and basic training provided to 10 Correctional Officers; 
2. No classification or assessment of inmates carried out and no guidelines in place;
3. Present estimated capacity of Correctional Services is 1895;
4. Current prison population is 3314 whereof 1825 are on remand/trial; 
5. Limited industry available to inmates who are most time idle.
6. Archaic prisons rules still in place but process of drafting new correctional rules started with methodology agreed but additional resources and expertise required;
7. No basic human rights audit conducted; 
8. Limited access to healthcare by inmates especially vulnerable and adamant the poor; 
9. Lack of infrastructure and basic materials and equipment for the provision of primary healthcare; 
10. Limited number of dedicated counselors and social workers in place to assist in reformation and rehabilitation of inmates;</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2018-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2018-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Case Management System (CMS) in place in selected facilities;
2. Pilot assessment and classification tool developed and implemented in selected facilities;
3. Prison Courts pilot model consolidated and SOPs/MOUs agreed for the effective functioning of the Courts;
4. Industry Master plan commenced implementation, and X skills training facilities established and at least 500 m/f inmates engaged in production and earning scheme; 
5. Correctional Act and Prison Rules review finalised and presented to Parliament for approval; 
6. 70 % of National Human Rights Actions Plans implemented across the facilities providing improved respect for the Mandela Rules
7. At least 5 Human Rights Audits undertaken by the SLCS and follow-up workshop conducted to commence establishment of the Standard Inspection Department;
8. Over 7 correctional facilities infrastructure refurbished and conditions of detention improved;
9. Over 60 male and female counselors and social workers trained and has commenced the provision of psycho-social support to inmates with substance abuse.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. At least 1 Pilot assessment and classification tool developed and implemented in the Pademba Road Male and Freetown Female Correctional Facilities; 
2. MOUs developed and submitted to the Police and Judiciary for ensuring information sharing for strengthening the implementation of the classification tool;
3. Agricultural farm established at the Mafanta Facility (1), and 6 facilities have smaller farming activities established. Small scale carpentry and sewing industries have been further consolidated at Pademba Road facility;
4. Over 246 sentenced inmates (21 female and 225 male) and 73 SLCS Officers have been trained to effectively manage the Industries Programme and provide training and mentoring of inmates;
5. Correctional Act and Prison Rules review finalised and presented to Ministry of Internal Affairs for approval; 
6. Over 60 % of National Human Rights Actions Plans implemented across the facilities showing real changes in the treatment of inmates such as better quality of food and nutrition, hygiene, increased access with outside world, leisure activities ensuring increased respect for the Mandela Rules
7. At least 5 Human Rights Audits undertaken by the SLCS and follow-up workshop in planned for January 2019; 
8. At least 7 correctional facilities infrastructure refurbished and conditions of detention improved;
9. Over 30 Male and Female Counselors and Social Workers has received training and has commenced the provision of psycho-social support to inmates with substance abuse.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Case Management System (CMS) in place in selected facilities by 28 February 2019;
2. At least 1 Correctional Facility fully refurbished in Waterloo allowing for the transfer of court going inmates and decongesting the maximum security facility in Freetown; 
3. At least 1 human rights action planning workshop held providing key recommendations to implement the Correctional Service Standard Inspections Department;
4. Revised Correctional Act and Prison Rules presented to Parliament for approval.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Justice App successfully updated to Version 2 and 75 tablets redistributed to Magistrate and High Courts. 
2. Waterloo Correctional Facility fully refurbished and populated by the end of September
3. At least 1 human right action planning workshop held in March 2019 benefiting 40 SLCS staff who discussed progress made on the Human Rights Action Plan in all centers.
4. Correctional Act and Prison Rules presently with the MOJ for review before presentation to Parliament.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
